		<div class="listing-header">
										<h1>General</h1>
				
						<br class="cl"/>
		</div> 
		<div id="listing-items">
			
							
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/GWP-ToolBox-for-Integrated-Water-Resources-Management" title="GWP ToolBox for Integrated Water Resources Management" alt="document">GWP ToolBox for Integrated Water Resources Management</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
The ToolBox of the Global Water Program allows water-related professionals to analyse the various elements of the IWRM process and facilitates the prioritization of actions aimed at improving the water governance and management. Altogether it contains close to 50 different tools. The Tools are illustrated by real case experience. The cases have been submitted by professionals from all over the world and offer realistic lessons for others by giving examples of how a tool has worked in a given combination and context. In addition, all the tools and cases are linked to reference materials: websites, references, organisations. The ToolBox organizes the tools into three types: (1) those which create the ‘enabling environment’, the laws, investments and policies which are the framework for other tools; (2) the building of appropriate institutions, and building capacity within these institutions; and finally (3) management tools, all of which can be used in an IWRM way.<a href="http://www.gwptoolbox.org/" target="_blank">Read the document.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/GWP-ToolBox-for-Integrated-Water-Resources-Management">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Water-resources" title="Water resources" alt="document">Water resources</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
The water portfolio of the International Development Association (IDA) is outlined. Its strategy is guided by the 2003 Water Resources Sector Strategy. Total IDA funding for 56 projects with WRM components amounted to about US$2.5 billion from 2000 to 2006. The impact of water resource management projects is often profound. Evidence from recent lending demonstrates such support has increased agricultural incomes, reduced the losses from flooding, nurtured regional cooperation, reduced sediment loadings and mitigated water-borne diseases. Case studies are included of work in: (1) the Senegal River Basin; (2) flood control in Yemen; (3) comprehensive water management in Tamil Nadu, India; and (4) the reversal of degradation in China’s Loess Plateau.<a href="http://siteresources.worldbank.org/IDA/Resources/IDA-Water-Resources.pdf" target="_blank">Read the Document.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Water-resources">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/World-water-and-food-to-2025" title="World water and food to 2025" alt="document">World water and food to 2025</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
By analysing various policy and investment scenarios, the authors of this book show how policymakers and water users that manage this scarce resource can help make the difference between a food-secure world and one in which water shortages could lead to hunger, poverty, and conflict. With better water management, sound policies, and increased investment in water, farmers and other water users can get more use out of each unit of water and the amount of water reserved for the environment can increase substantially. The following key questions are answered: (1) How will water availability and demand evolve over the next three decades, accounting for availability and variability in water resources, water supply infrastructure, and irrigation and non-agricultural water demands? (2) How will water scarcity affect food production and the availability of water for environmental purposes? (3) How much of future food production will come from rainfed and irrigated areas? And (4) what are the impacts of alternative water policies and investments on water supply and demand, food production and demand, and food security.<a href="http://www.ifpri.org/pubs/books/water2025/water2025.pdf" target="_blank">Read the document.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/World-water-and-food-to-2025">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Balancing-water-uses" title="Balancing water uses" alt="document">Balancing water uses</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
In this thematic background paper for the International Conference on Freshwater (Bonn, Germany), an overview is presented of the current state of water use, success stories in water management, lessons learned, issues, and policy implications for achieving good global water governance. The relevance of rainfed agriculture to global food and water security is emphasized. With increasing water scarcity, it is essential to view water allocation and distribution among users from a basin perspective. There is a need to increase global investment in water security by US$ 100 billion/year. Other major policy issues are capacity building for integrated water resources management and the co-management of water for agriculture and for nature. In order to achieve both food and environmental security simultaneously by 2025, water productivity would have to increase by 60% for irrigated land and by 30% for rainfed land, which is about double the normal increase.<a href="http://www.riverbasin.org/view_file.cfm?fileid=191" target="_blank">For more information.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Balancing-water-uses">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/World-Water-Vision-Report" title="World Water Vision Report " alt="document">World Water Vision Report </a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
The vision promulgated for 2025 is one in which all people have access to safe and sufficient water resources to meet their needs, including food, in ways that maintain the integrity of freshwater ecosystems. The actions needed are identified and responsibilities for implementation are made clear. Major avenues for improvement include: (1) expanding irrigated agriculture; (2) increasing water productivity; (3) developing biotechnology for agriculture; (4) increasing storage; (5) reforming water resource management institutions; (6) valuing ecosystem functions; (7) increasing cooperation in international basins; and (8) supporting innovation. Recommendations are made to achieve an increase of global annual investments to over US$ 100 billion/year.<a href="http://www.worldwatercouncil.org/index.php?id=961" target="_blank">For more information.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/World-Water-Vision-Report">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Water-for-food-water-for-life" title="Water for food, water for life" alt="document">Water for food, water for life</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
The Comprehensive Assessment of Water Management in Agriculture (CA) is an innovative multi-institute process aimed at identifying existing knowledge and stimulating thought on ways to manage water resources to continue meeting the needs of both humans and ecosystems. The CA critically evaluates the benefits, costs, and impacts of the past 50 years of water development and challenges to water management currently facing communities. It assesses innovative solutions and explores consequences of potential investment and management decisions. The CA is designed as a learning process, engaging networks of stakeholders to produce knowledge synthesis and methodologies. The main output of the CA is an assessment report that aims to guide investment and management decisions in the near future considering their impact over the next 50 years in order to enhance food and environmental security to support the achievement of the MDGs.<a href="http://www.iwmi.cgiar.org/assessment/" target="_blank">For more information.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Water-for-food-water-for-life">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Reuse-of-wastewater-in-agriculture" title="Reuse of wastewater in agriculture" alt="document">Reuse of wastewater in agriculture</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
These UNDP-World Bank guidelines summarize information on the reuse of wastewater for irrigation. They integrate the World Health Organization health guidelines for the reuse of wastewater with the FAO water quality guidelines for irrigation. The report provides guidance for choosing among technical and policy options and it proposes a framework for inclusion of economic and financial considerations. Properly designed, wastewater reuse is an environmental protection measure that is superior to discharging treated wastewater into surface waters. The guidelines suggest consideration of land application as a disposal option even where no urgent need for additional sources of irrigation water exists. The necessary close collaboration between the sectors involved (agriculture, water, wastes, environmental protection, health) raises a number of institutional issues that are reviewed in these guidelines.<a href="http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/WDSP/IB/1994/04/01/000009265_3961006165519/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf" target="_blank">Read the document.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Reuse-of-wastewater-in-agriculture">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Integrated-resource-recovery." title="Integrated resource recovery. " alt="document">Integrated resource recovery. </a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
This report summarizes information on practices of wastewater reuse for agriculture in developing and developed countries around the world and reviews the public health and technological aspects of irrigation with wastewater. A theoretical model is developed to assist in predicting the degree of risk of disease transmission associated with various wastewater reuse practices. Unrestricted wastewater irrigation could be based on an effluent with less than one nematode egg (Ascaris or Trichuris) per litre and a geometric mean coliform concentration of 1000/100 ml. Multicell stabilization ponds with 20 days’ detention time effectively remove bacterial, viral, and helminth pathogens in a low-cost, robust, easy-to-operate system that is especially suitable for developing countries. This study provides a rational basis for the development of a sound economic approach to wastewater irrigation in developing countries.<a href="http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/WDSP/IB/1999/09/17/000178830_98101904164938/Rendered/PDF/multi_page.pdf" target="_blank">Read the document.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Integrated-resource-recovery.">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Aquaponics-integration-of-hydroponics-with-aquaculture" title="Aquaponics: integration of hydroponics with aquaculture" alt="document">Aquaponics: integration of hydroponics with aquaculture</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>By Steve Diver. Aquaponics is a bio-integrated system that links recirculating aquaculture with hydroponic vegetable, flower, and/or herb production. Recent advances by researchers and growers alike have turned aquaponics into a working model of sustainable food production. This publication provides an introduction to aquaponics with brief profiles of working units around the country. An extensive list of resources point the reader to print and Web-based educational materials for further technical assistance.</p>
							<p><span class="date">29/05/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Aquaponics-integration-of-hydroponics-with-aquaculture">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
											</div> 	
	<br class="cl"/>
